<DOC><DOCNO> ZF32-070-112 </DOCNO><DOCID>11 188 755</DOCID><JOURNAL>Home Office Computing  Sept 1991 v9 n9 p22(1).andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>Five ways technology pays for itself. (obtaining the technologyneeded to run home-based businesses)</TITLE><AUTHOR>Edwards, Paul; Edwards, Sarah.andM;</AUTHOR><TEXT><ABSTRACT>Home-based business owners intent on success need to determinetheir computer hardware and software needs and to purchaseequipment that can help them meet their business objectives.andP;  Somebusiness owners continually wait for the 'perfect' time to buyequipment, but the sooner users upgrade, the sooner they will seebenefits.andP;  Small business owners can obtain help in setting upequipment by using consultants or by contacting equipmentdistributors.andP;  The technology will eventually pay for itself whenbuying new software and equipment, and will cost less thancontinuing with old operations methods.andP;  New technology will freeup time for marketing and advertising and new equipment can alsoattract business.andP;  Upgrading also makes smart business sense whenthe cost of hardware or software is self-liquidating and when newequipment will generate income by itself.andM;</ABSTRACT></TEXT><DESCRIPT>Topic:     Goals and ObjectivesHome-based businessesStrategic PlanningSmall businessUpgradingGuidelinesCost of Operation.andM;</DESCRIPT></DOC>